To investigate whether cellular senescence-induced changes in phase behavior were also evident in other nuclear condensates beyond nucleoli, we first observed U2OS cells stably expressing green fluorescent protein (GFP)-attached Non-POU domain containing octamer-binding protein (NONO), a well-characterized paraspeckle protein (Fig. S1A). As previously described, NONO-GFP expressing U2OS cells treated with etoposide, a topoisomerase II inhibitor, showed evident signs of cellular senescence such as increase in both activity of senescence-associated β-galactosidase and expression of p21 (Fig. S2) [14, 16]. Etoposide-affected senescent cells displayed both increased numbers and area fractions of NONO foci (Fig. S1A–C). To examine the localized abundance of NONO-GFP at foci relative to the dilute surrounding, we defined the fluorescence coexistence index (FCI) as \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\frac{{I}_{\text{foci}}}{{I}_{\text{foci}}+{I}_{\text{dilute}}}$$\end{document}IfociIfoci+Idilute, where Ifoci and Idilute represent the integrated intensity of each phase. In a two-phase regime, the FCI value closer to 1 implies that a larger proportion of molecules are localized to foci, whereas a value closer to 0 signifies that more molecules are dispersed in the dilute phase. In accordance with the higher numbers and area fractions of NONO-GFP foci, the FCI values were also elevated in senescent cells (Fig. S1D–F). Furthermore, we revealed that genotoxic stress-induced senescence can establish an environment where incorporation of NONO-GFP into foci was favored, particularly to the cells expressing more NONO-GFP, as indicated by the steeper slope in our Ifoci + Idilute − FCI plot (Fig. S1G). To corroborate these findings with biochemical approaches, we carried out the Western blotting to measure the cellular amounts of NONO-GFP. The expression of NONO-GFP was elevated under cellular senescence, aligning with imaging analysis (Fig. S3).

